data.content:
Three breaking changes hit your code. Here's each one:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — no longer accepts expression trees

The parameter changed from `Expression<Func<SetPropertyCalls<Blog>, ...>>` to a plain `Func`. Your manual expression tree code **won't compile**. Replace with the much simpler inline lambda:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No more `Expression.Lambda`, `Expression.Call`, etc. — conditional logic goes directly in the lambda body now.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two changes

**a) Sibling complex types now get uniquified columns.** Previously `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` could silently share one `Street` column (data corruption risk). Now EF appends a number (`Street`, `Street1`). To keep existing column names, set them explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});
```

**b) Nested complex types now use the full path.** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` used to produce column `BillingAddress_City`, now it produces `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. To preserve the old name:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

> **Either** add explicit `HasColumnName` to preserve existing schema, **or** generate a new migration and apply the rename.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

All methods (`CommandReaderExecuting`, `CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) now require an additional `string logCommandText` parameter for redacted SQL logging:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (constants may be redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual SQL
    }
}
```

This supports EF 10's new constant-redaction feature — `logCommandText` has sensitive inlined values scrubbed unless `EnableSensitiveDataLogging()` is on.
